            "word": "fox"
        },
        {
            "end": 12.85,
            "features": [
                "sos"
            ],
            "start": 12.79,
            "word": "walking"
        },
        {
            "end": 12.85,
            "features": [
                "sos"
            ],
            "start": 12.79,
            "word": "in"
        },
        {
            "end": 12.85,
            "features": [
                "sos"
            ],
            "start": 12.79,
            "word": "the"
        },
        {
            "end": 12.85,
            "features": [
                "sos"
            ],
            "start": 12.79,
            "word": "woods"
        }
    ]
}
`

using the below schema:

`
schema = Schema(
    {
        Required('wordObjects'): [
            {
                'start': float,
                'end': float,
                'word': str,
                'features': [str],
            }
        ]
    }
)
`

However I keep getting an error saying that 
`
{
  "error": "expected str @ data[u'wordObjects'][0][u'features'][0]"
}
`

However clearly it is already a string, I am pretty lost here. Please if you guys could point out what I'm doing wrong, or maybe I found a bug with nested objects

Here's the offending line:

    CPM_unpaired_tmp   = np.eye(Zc, dtype=int);
E: function uses an unkown (sic) (or unsupported) keyword argument `dtype` (nr_encoder.py, line 75)

I think there is a bug in the `SceneCombiner::CopyScene` function at [line 1024](https://github.com/assimp/assimp/blob/master/code/SceneCombiner.cpp#L1026). As it is mentioned in the comment there the source scene might have `src->mPrivate` equal to `NULL`. As a result you the program crashes at line 1024 when `src->mPrivate` is cast to `const ScenePrivateData*` and member `mPPStepsApplied` is set to 0.

Here is a fix that worked for me:
```C++
  if (ScenePriv(src))
    ScenePriv(dest)->mPPStepsApplied = ScenePriv(src)->mPPStepsApplied;
  else
  {
    dest->mPrivate = new Assimp::ScenePrivateData();
    ScenePriv(dest)->mPPStepsApplied = 0;
  }
```

On aarch64, the libraries is not the same as the 32bit counter part.
This tries to fix the problem.
`
--- pythonforandroid/bootstraps/sdl2/build/src/main/java/org/kivy/android/PythonUtil.java
+++ pythonforandroid/bootstraps/sdl2/build/src/main/java/org/kivy/android/PythonUtil.java
@@ -10,6 +10,21 @@ import java.util.regex.Pattern;
 public class PythonUtil {
        private static final String TAG = "pythonutil";
 
+    protected static String getLibLocation(File filesDir) {
+        String[] libLocations = {
+            filesDir.getAbsolutePath() + "/lib/",
+            filesDir.getParentFile().getParentFile().getAbsolutePath() + "/lib/",
+            filesDir.getParentFile().getAbsolutePath() + "/lib/"
+        };
+        for (String libloc : libLocations) {
+            File dir = new File(libloc);
+            if(dir.exists() && dir.isDirectory()) {
+                return libloc;
+            }
+        }
+        return filesDir.getAbsolutePath();
+    }
+
     protected static void addLibraryIfExists(ArrayList<String> libsList, String pattern, File libsDir) {
         // pattern should be the name of the lib file, without the
         // preceding "lib" or suffix ".so", for instance "ssl.*" will
@@ -31,7 +46,7 @@ public class PythonUtil {
 
     protected static ArrayList<String> getLibraries(File filesDir) {
 
-        String libsDirPath = filesDir.getParentFile().getParentFile().getAbsolutePath() + "/lib/";
+        String libsDirPath = getLibLocation(filesDir);
         File libsDir = new File(libsDirPath);
 
         ArrayList<String> libsList = new ArrayList<String>();
`

