TL;DR: When accessing and modiyfing a singleton class through python scripts evaluated with py::eval, Ubuntu (14/16) maintains a single object between the C++ and Python layer, while Windows appears to duplicate the object.

I have a singleton class that I have wrapped with pybind.  I am also trying trying to access and modify this class through the pybind interpreter.  Since I want to support arbitrary code execution of scripts and files I am using py::eval.  Say I have modified the singleton class in C++, then later call py::eval on a script that accesses this singleton class. On Ubuntu, the same singleton object is shared between the C++ and Python layer, and changes to the object are shared.  On Windows, no changes persist between the layers.

Given the code below, the output on Ubuntu is:
```
C++: Foo is 2
Python: Foo is 2
Python: Foo is 3
C++: Foo is 3
```
And on Windows 
```
C++: Foo is 2
Python: Foo is 0
Python: Foo is 3
C++: Foo is 2
```

I have tried Python 2.7 and 3.4 on Windows.  And 2.7, 3.4, 3.4, 3.6 on Ubuntu.  For compiling on Windows I have tried MSVC 2015 and 2017.  On Ubuntu I have tried gcc 5.x and 6.x.  The results have been the same.  I am under the assumption this is an issue with how libraries are being loaded, and how that is handled differently between the two operating systems.  However I don't have much more to go on than that.  Is there an obvious mistake being made here?  If not is there a direction I can explore to work on resolving this?

#### Reproducible example code

main.cpp
```
#include <pybind11/embed.h>
#include "Foo.h"
#include <iostream>
namespace py = pybind11;
using namespace std;
int main() {
	py::scoped_interpreter guard{};
	Foo::get().setVal(2);
	cout << "C++: Foo is " << Foo::get().getVal() << endl;
	py::object globals = py::module::import("__main__").attr("__dict__");
	py::object locals = py::dict();
	py::eval<py::eval_statements>(R"(
				import Foo_Py
				print('Python: Foo is ' + str(Foo_Py.Foo.get().getValue()))
				Foo_Py.Foo.get().setValue(3)
				print('Python: Foo is ' + str(Foo_Py.Foo.get().getValue()))

			)", globals, locals);

	cout << "C++: Foo is " << Foo::get().getVal() << endl;
}
```
Foo_Py.cpp
```
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include "Foo.h"
#include <memory>
using namespace std;
namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(Foo_Py) {
	py::module m("Foo_Py");
	py::class_<Foo, unique_ptr<Foo, py::nodelete>>(m, "Foo")
		.def_static("get", &Foo::get, py::return_value_policy::reference)
		.def("getValue", &Foo::getVal)
		.def("setValue", &Foo::setVal);

	return m.ptr();
}

```
Foo.h
```
#pragma once
#include <memory>
using namespace std;
class Foo {
public:
	static Foo& get();
	int getVal() const;
	void setVal(int v);
protected:
	Foo();
	~Foo();
private:
	int _val;
};
```
Foo.cpp
```
#pragma once
#include "Foo.h"
using namespace std;

Foo &Foo::get() {
	static Foo _instance;
	return _instance;
}
int Foo::getVal() const { return _val; }
void Foo::setVal(int v) { _val = v; }
Foo::Foo() : _val(0) {}
Foo::~Foo() {}
```


